[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The principal designers of the C# programming language were Anders Hejlsberg, Scott Wiltamuth, and Peter Golde from Microsoft.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] It was first widely distributed in July 2000 and was later approved as an international standard by Ecma (ECMA-334) in 2002 and ISO/IEC (ISO/IEC 23270 and 20619) in 2003.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft introduced C# along with .NET Framework and Microsoft Visual Studio, both of which are, technically speaking, closed-source.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] At the time, Microsoft had no open-source products.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Four years later, in 2004, a free and open-source project called Mono began, providing a cross-platform compiler and runtime environment for the C# programming language.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] A decade later, Microsoft released Visual Studio Code (code editor), Roslyn (compiler), and the unified .NET platform (software framework), all of which support C# and are free, open-source, and cross-platform.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Mono also joined Microsoft, but was not merged into .NET.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] As of November 2025, the most recent stable version of the language is C# 14.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] During the development of the .NET Framework, the class libraries were originally written using a managed code compiler system named *Simple Managed C* (SMC).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In January 1999, Anders Hejlsberg formed a team to build a new language at the time called COOL, which stood for "C-like Object Oriented Language".
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft had considered keeping the name "COOL(C-like Object Oriented Language)" as the final name of the language, but chose not to do so for trademark reasons.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] By the time the .NET project was publicly announced at the July 2000 Professional Developers Conference, the language had been renamed C#, and the class libraries and ASP.NET runtime were ported to C#.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Hejlsberg was C#'s principal designer and lead architect at Microsoft, and had been previously involved with the design of Turbo Pascal, Embarcadero Delphi (formerly CodeGear Delphi, Inprise Delphi and Borland Delphi), and Visual J++.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In interviews and technical papers, he has stated that flaws in most major programming languages (e.g.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C++, Java, Delphi, and Smalltalk) drove the fundamentals of the Common Language Runtime (CLR), which, in turn, drove the design of the C# language.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In July 2000, Hejlsberg said that C# is "not a Java clone" and is "much closer to C++" in its design.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Since the release of C# 2.0 in November 2005, the C# and Java languages have evolved on increasingly divergent trajectories, becoming two quite different languages.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] One of the first major departures came with the addition of generics to both languages, with vastly different implementations.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# uses reification to provide "first-class" generic objects that can be used like any other class, with code generation performed at class-load time.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has also added several major features to accommodate functional-style programming, culminating in the LINQ extensions released with C# 3.0 and its supporting framework of lambda expressions, extension methods, and anonymous types.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] These features enable C# programmers to use functional programming techniques, such as closures, when it is advantageous to their application.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# used to have a mascot called Andy (named after Anders Hejlsberg).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# was originally submitted to the ISO/IEC JTC 1 subcommittee SC 22 for review, under ISO/IEC 23270:2003, was withdrawn and was then approved under ISO/IEC 23270:2006.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The 23270:2006 is withdrawn under 23270:2018 and approved with this version.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft first used the name C# in 1988 for a variant of the C language designed for incremental compilation.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] That project was not completed, and the name was later reused.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The name "C sharp" was inspired by the musical notation whereby a sharp symbol indicates that the written note should be made a semitone higher in pitch.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This is similar to the language name of C++, where "++" indicates that a variable should be incremented by 1 after being evaluated.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The sharp symbol also resembles a ligature of four "+" symbols (in a two-by-two grid), further implying that the language is an increment of C++.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Due to technical limits of display (standard fonts, browsers, etc.), and most keyboard layouts lacking a sharp symbol (U+266F ♯ MUSIC SHARP SIGN (&sharp;)), the number sign (U+0023 # NUMBER SIGN (&num;)) was chosen to approximate the sharp symbol in the written name of the programming language.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This convention is reflected in the ECMA-334 C# Language Specification.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The "sharp" suffix has been used by a number of other Microsoft .NET compatible/compliant languages that are variants of existing languages, including J# (a .NET language also designed by Microsoft that is derived from Java 1.1), A# (from Ada), and the functional programming language F#.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The original implementation of Eiffel for .NET was called Eiffel#, a name retired since the full Eiffel language is now supported.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The suffix has also been used for libraries, such as Gtk# (a .NET wrapper for GTK and other GNOME libraries) and Cocoa# (a wrapper for Cocoa).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Development of the text for standards (beginning with C# 6) is done on GitHub.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# 7 was submitted to Ecma and approved in December 2023.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] As of January 2024, the standard for C# 8 is currently under development, referencing the approved language proposals.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] By design, C# is the programming language that most directly reflects the underlying Common Language Infrastructure (CLI).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Most of its intrinsic types correspond to value-types implemented by the CLI framework.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] However, the language specification does not state the code generation requirements of the compiler: that is, it does not state that a C# compiler must target a Common Language Runtime (CLR), or generate Common Intermediate Language (CIL), or generate any other specific format.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Some C# compilers can also generate machine code like traditional compilers of Objective-C, C, C++, Assembly and Fortran.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# supports strongly, implicitly typed variable declarations with the keyword `var`, and implicitly typed arrays with the keyword `new[]` followed by a collection initializer.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Due to their special handling of the equality operator and their immutability, strings will nevertheless behave as if they were values, for all practical purposes.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The programmer can even use them as case labels.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Where necessary, value types will be boxed automatically.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# supports a strict Boolean data type, `bool`.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Statements that take conditions, such as `while` and `if`, require an expression of a type that evaluates to the `true` boolean value.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] While C++ also has a Boolean type, it can be freely converted to and from integers, and expressions such as `if (a)` require only that `a` is convertible to bool, allowing `a` to be an int, or a pointer.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# disallows this "integer meaning true or false" approach, on the grounds that forcing programmers to use expressions that return exactly `bool` can prevent certain types of programming mistakes such as `if (a = b)` (use of assignment `=` instead of equality `==`).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The only implicit conversions by default are those that are considered safe, such as widening of integers.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This is enforced at compile-time, during Just-in-time compilation, and, in some cases, at runtime.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] No implicit conversions occur between Booleans and integers, nor between enumeration members and integers (except for literal 0, which can be implicitly converted to any enumerated type).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Any user-defined conversion must be explicitly marked as explicit or implicit, unlike C++ copy constructors and conversion operators, which are both implicit by default.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has explicit support for covariance and contravariance in generic types, unlike C++ which has some degree of support for contravariance simply through the semantics of return types on virtual methods.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Enumeration members are placed in their own scope.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The C# language does not allow for global variables or functions.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] All methods and members must be declared within classes.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Static members of public classes can substitute for global variables and functions.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Local variables cannot shadow variables of the enclosing block, unlike C and C++, but may shadow type-level names.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] A *method* in C# is a member of a class that can be invoked as a function, rather than the mere value-holding capability of a *field*, i.e., class or instance variable.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Different from most other languages, call-by-reference parameters have to be marked both at the function definition and at the calling site, and the programmer can choose between `ref` and `out`, the latter allowing handing over an uninitialized variable which will have a definite value on return.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Additionally, the programmer can specify a variable-sized argument list by applying the `params` keyword to the last parameter.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Certain specific kinds of methods, such as those that simply get or set a field's value by returning or assigning it, do not require an explicitly stated full signature, but in the general case, the definition of a class includes the full signature declaration of its methods.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Like C++, and unlike Java, C# programmers must use the scope modifier keyword `virtual` to allow methods to be overridden by subclasses.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike C++, the programmer must explicitly specify the keyword `override` when doing so.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This is supposed to avoid confusion between overriding and newly overloading a function, i.e., hiding the former implementation.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] To do the latter, the programmer has to specify the `new` keyword.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The keyword `sealed` can be used to disallow further overrides for individual methods or whole classes.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The type `dynamic` allows for run-time method binding, allowing for JavaScript-like method calls and run-time object composition.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has support for strongly-typed function pointers via the keyword `delegate`.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Like the Qt framework's pseudo-C++ *signal* and *slot*, C# has semantics specifically surrounding publish-subscribe style events, though C# uses delegates to do so.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike fields, `event` variables can be part of an interface, because they technically consist of two default functions to add and remove to-be-called delegates.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# offers Java-like `synchronized` method calls, via the attribute `[MethodImpl(MethodImplOptions.Synchronized)]`, and has support for mutually-exclusive locks via the keyword `lock`.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The properties can be simple accessor functions with a backing field, or implement arbitrary getter and setter functions.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] A property is read-only if there's no setter.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Like with fields, there can be class and instance properties.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The underlying methods can be `virtual` or `abstract` like any other method.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Since C# 3.0 the syntactic sugar of auto-implemented properties is available, where the accessor (getter) and mutator (setter) encapsulate operations on a single field of a class.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] A C# `namespace` provides the same level of code isolation as a Java `package` or a C++ `namespace`, with rules and features very similar to a `package`.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Namespaces can be imported with the "using" syntax.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In C#, memory address pointers can only be used within blocks specifically marked as *unsafe*, and programs with unsafe code need appropriate permissions to run.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Most object access is done through safe object references, which always either point to a "live" object or have the well-defined null value; it is impossible to obtain a reference to a "dead" object (one that has been garbage collected), or to an arbitrary block of memory.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] An unsafe pointer can point to an instance of an unmanaged value type that does not contain any references to objects subject to garbage collections such as class instances, arrays or strings.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Code that is not marked as unsafe can still store and manipulate pointers through the `System.IntPtr` type, but it cannot dereference them.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Managed memory cannot be explicitly freed; instead, it is automatically garbage collected.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Garbage collection addresses the problem of memory leaks by freeing the programmer of responsibility for releasing memory that is no longer needed in most cases.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Code that retains references to objects longer than is required can still experience higher memory usage than necessary, however once the final reference to an object is released the memory is available for garbage collection.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] A range of standard exceptions are available to programmers.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Methods in standard libraries regularly throw system exceptions in some circumstances and the range of exceptions thrown is normally documented.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Custom exception classes can be defined for classes allowing handling to be put in place for particular circumstances as needed.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This is usually called a "try-catch" code block, because of the "try" and "catch" functions being used and accessible on all C# versions.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] If inspecting the error details is not required, the `(Exception ex)` parameter can be omitted as well.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Also, there can be several "catch" parts handling different kinds of exceptions.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Checked exceptions are not present in C# (in contrast to Java).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This has been a conscious decision based on the issues of scalability and version management.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike C++, C# does not support multiple inheritance, although a class can implement any number of "interfaces" (fully abstract classes).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This was a design decision by the language's lead architect to avoid complications and to simplify architectural requirements throughout CLI.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] When implementing multiple interfaces that contain a method with the same name and taking parameters of the same types in the same order, i.e., the same signature, similar to Java, C# allows both a single method to cover all interfaces and, if necessary, specific methods for each interface.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# also offers function overloading (a.k.a. ad-hoc-polymorphism), i.e., methods with the same name, but distinguishable signatures.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike Java, C# additionally supports operator overloading.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Since version 2.0, C# offers parametric polymorphism, i.e., classes with arbitrary or constrained type parameters, e.g., `List<T>`, a variable-sized array which only can contain elements of type `T`.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] There are certain kinds of constraints the programmer can specify for the type parameters: Has to be type X (or one derived from it), has to implement a certain interface, has to be a reference type, has to be a value type, has to implement a public parameterless constructor.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Most of them can be combined, and any number of interfaces can be specified.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# has the ability to utilize LINQ through the .NET Framework.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] A developer can query a variety of data sources, provided the `IEnumerable<T>` interface is implemented on the object.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This includes XML documents, an ADO.NET dataset, and SQL databases.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Using LINQ in C# brings advantages like IntelliSense support, strong filtering capabilities, type safety with compile error checking ability, and consistency for querying data over a variety of sources.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] There are several different language structures that can be utilized with C# and LINQ and they are query expressions, lambda expressions, anonymous types, implicitly typed variables, extension methods, and object initializers.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] LINQ has two syntaxes: query syntax and method syntax.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] However, the compiler always converts the query syntax to method syntax at compile time.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This unified type system is called Common Type System (CTS).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] A unified type system implies that all types, including primitives such as integers, are subclasses of the `System.Object` class.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] For example, every type inherits a `ToString()` method.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Instances of value types neither have referential identity nor referential comparison semantics.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Equality and inequality comparisons for value types compare the actual data values within the instances, unless the corresponding operators are overloaded.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Value types are derived from `System.ValueType`, always have a default value, and can always be created and copied.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Other examples are `enum` (enumerations) and `struct` (user defined structures).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In contrast, reference types have the notion of referential identity, meaning that each instance of a reference type is inherently distinct from every other instance, even if the data within both instances is the same.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This is reflected in default equality and inequality comparisons for reference types, which test for referential rather than structural equality, unless the corresponding operators are overloaded (such as the case for `System.String`).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Some operations are not always possible, such as creating an instance of a reference type, copying an existing instance, or performing a value comparison on two existing instances.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Nevertheless, specific reference types can provide such services by exposing a public constructor or implementing a corresponding interface (such as `ICloneable` or `IComparable`).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Examples of reference types are `object` (the ultimate base class for all other C# classes), `System.String` (a string of Unicode characters), and `System.Array` (a base class for all C# arrays).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Both type categories are extensible with user-defined types.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The C# specification details a minimum set of types and class libraries that the compiler expects to have available.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In practice, C# is most often used with some implementation of the Common Language Infrastructure (CLI), which is standardized as ECMA-335 *Common Language Infrastructure (CLI)*.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In addition to the standard CLI specifications, there are many commercial and community class libraries that build on top of the .NET framework libraries to provide additional functionality.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# can make calls to any library included in the List of .NET libraries and frameworks.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The line above imports all types in the `System` namespace.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] For example, the `Console` class used later in the source code is defined in the `System` namespace, meaning it can be used without supplying the full name of the type (which includes the namespace).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This line is a comment; it describes and documents the code for the programmer(s).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Above is a class definition for the `Program` class.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Everything that follows between the pair of braces describes that class.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The curly brackets demarcate the boundaries of a code block.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In this first instance, they are marking the start and end of the `Program` class.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This declares the class member method where the program begins execution.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The .NET runtime calls the `Main` method.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Unlike in Java, the `Main` method does not need the `public` keyword, which tells the compiler that the method can be called from anywhere by any class.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Writing `static void Main(string[] args)` is equivalent to writing `private static void Main(string[] args)`.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The static keyword makes the method accessible without an instance of `Program`.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Each console application's `Main` entry point must be declared `static` otherwise the program would require an instance of `Program`, but any instance would require a program.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] To avoid that irresolvable circular dependency, C# compilers processing console applications (like that above) report an error if there is no `static Main` method.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The `void` keyword declares that `Main` has no return value.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] `Console` is a static class in the `System` namespace.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] It provides an interface to the standard input/output, and error streams for console applications.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The program calls the `Console` method `WriteLine`, which displays on the console a line with the argument, the string `"Hello, World!"`.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] With .NET 2.0 and C# 2.0, the community got more flexible collections than those in .NET 1.x.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In the absence of generics, developers had to use collections such as ArrayList to store elements as objects of unspecified kind, which incurred performance overhead when boxing/unboxing/type-checking the contained items.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Generics introduced a massive new feature in .NET that allowed developers to create type-safe data structures.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] This shift is particularly important in the context of converting legacy systems, where updating to generics can significantly enhance performance and maintainability by replacing outdated data structures with more efficient, type-safe alternatives.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In August 2001, Microsoft, Hewlett-Packard and Intel co-sponsored the submission of specifications for C# as well as the Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) to the standards organization Ecma International.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In December 2001, ECMA released ECMA-334 *C# Language Specification*.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] C# became an ISO/IEC standard in 2003 (ISO/IEC 23270:2003 - *Information technology — Programming languages — C#*).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] ECMA had previously adopted equivalent specifications as the 2nd edition of C#, in December 2002.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In June 2005, ECMA approved edition 3 of the C# specification, and updated ECMA-334.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Additions included partial classes, anonymous methods, nullable types, and generics (somewhat similar to C++ templates).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] In July 2005, ECMA submitted to ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22, via the latter's Fast-Track process, the standards and related TRs.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The C# language definition and the CLI are standardized under ISO/IEC and Ecma standards that provide reasonable and non-discriminatory licensing protection from patent claims.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft initially agreed not to sue open-source developers for violating patents in non-profit projects for the part of the framework that is covered by the Open Specification Promise.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft has also agreed not to enforce patents relating to Novell products against Novell's paying customers with the exception of a list of products that do not explicitly mention C#, .NET or Novell's implementation of .NET (The Mono Project).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] However, Novell maintained that Mono does not infringe any Microsoft patents.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft also made a specific agreement not to enforce patent rights related to the Moonlight browser plugin, which depends on Mono, provided it is obtained through Novell.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] A decade later, Microsoft began developing free, open-source, and cross-platform tooling for C#, namely Visual Studio Code, .NET Core, and Roslyn.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Mono joined Microsoft as a project of Xamarin, a Microsoft subsidiary.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Microsoft has developed open-source reference C# compilers and tools.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The first compiler, Roslyn, compiles into intermediate language (IL), and the second one, RyuJIT, is a JIT (just-in-time) compiler, which is dynamic and does on-the-fly optimization and compiles the IL into native code for the front-end of the CPU.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] RyuJIT is open source and written in C++.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] Roslyn is entirely written in managed code (C#), has been opened up and functionality surfaced as APIs.
