[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/c-sharp-programming-language] The Godot game engine has implemented an optional C# module due to a donation of $24,000 from Microsoft.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/data-binding] In computer programming, **data-binding** is a general technique that binds data sources from the provider and consumer together and synchronizes them.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/data-binding] This is usually done with two data/information sources with different languages, as in XML data binding and UI data binding.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/data-binding] In UI data binding, data and information objects of the same language, but different logic function are bound together (e.g., Java UI elements to Java objects).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/data-binding] In a data binding process, each data change is reflected automatically by the elements that are bound to the data.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/data-binding] The term data binding is also used in cases where an outer representation of data in an element changes, and the underlying data is automatically updated to reflect this change.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/data-binding] As an example, a change in a `TextBox` element could modify the underlying data value.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] JSON is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] It was derived from JavaScript, but many modern programming languages include code to generate and parse JSON-format data.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] JSON filenames use the extension `.json`.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Douglas Crockford originally specified the JSON format in the early 2000s.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] They and Chip Morningstar sent the first JSON message in April 2001.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] The 2017 international standard (ECMA-404 and ISO/IEC 21778:2017) specifies that "JSON" is "pronounced /ˈdʒeɪ.sən/, as in 'Jason and The Argonauts'".
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] The first (2013) edition of ECMA-404 did not address the pronunciation.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Crockford said in 2011, "There's a lot of argument about how you pronounce that, but I strictly don't care." /ˈdʒeɪˌsɒn/ is another common pronunciation.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] After RFC 4627 had been available as its "informational" specification since 2006, JSON was first standardized in 2013, as ECMA-404.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] RFC 8259, published in 2017, is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90, and it remains consistent with ECMA-404.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] That same year, JSON was also standardized as ISO/IEC 21778:2017.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] The ECMA and ISO/IEC standards describe only the allowed syntax, whereas the RFC covers some security and interoperability considerations.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] JSON grew out of a need for a real-time server-to-browser session communication protocol without using browser plugins such as Flash or Java applets, the dominant methods used in the early 2000s.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Crockford first specified and popularized the JSON format.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] The acronym originated at State Software, a company cofounded by Crockford and others in March 2001.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] The cofounders had a round-table discussion and voted on whether to call the data format JSML (JavaScript Markup Language) or JSON (JavaScript Object Notation), as well as under what license type to make it available.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] The JSON.org website was launched in 2001.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] In December 2005, Yahoo! began offering some of its Web services in JSON.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] A precursor to the JSON libraries was used in a children's digital asset trading game project named Cartoon Orbit at Communities.com which used a browser side plug-in with a proprietary messaging format to manipulate DHTML elements.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Crockford then found that JavaScript could be used as an object-based messaging format for such a system.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] The system was sold to Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, and EDS.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] JSON was based on a subset of the JavaScript scripting language (specifically, Standard ECMA-262 3rd Edition—December 1999) and is commonly used with JavaScript, but it is a language-independent data format.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Code for parsing and generating JSON data is readily available in many programming languages.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] JSON's website lists JSON libraries by language.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] In October 2013, Ecma International published the first edition of its JSON standard ECMA-404.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] That same year, RFC 7158 used ECMA-404 as a reference.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] In 2014, RFC 7159 became the main reference for JSON's Internet uses, superseding RFC 4627 and RFC 7158 (but preserving ECMA-262 and ECMA-404 as main references).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] In November 2017, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22 published ISO/IEC 21778:2017 as an international standard.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] On December 13, 2017, the Internet Engineering Task Force obsoleted RFC 7159 when it published RFC 8259, which is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Crockford added a clause to the JSON license stating, "The Software shall be used for Good, not Evil", in order to open-source the JSON libraries while mocking corporate lawyers and those who are overly pedantic.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] On the other hand, this clause led to license compatibility problems of the JSON license with other open-source licenses since open-source software and free software usually imply no restrictions on the purpose of use.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] The following example shows a possible JSON representation describing a person.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] This is a consequence of JSON disallowing only "control characters".
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] For maximum portability, these characters are backslash-escaped.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] JSON exchange in an open ecosystem must be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] The encoding supports the full Unicode character set, including those characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (U+0000 to U+FFFF).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] However, if escaped, those characters must be written using UTF-16 surrogate pairs.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] JSON became a strict subset of ECMAScript as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Whitespace is allowed and ignored around or between syntactic elements (values and punctuation, but not within a string value).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Four specific characters are considered whitespace for this purpose: space, horizontal tab, line feed, and carriage return.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] In particular, the byte order mark must not be generated by a conforming implementation (though it may be accepted when parsing JSON).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] JSON does not provide syntax for comments.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Early versions of JSON (such as specified by RFC 4627) required that a valid JSON text must consist of only an object or an array type, which could contain other types within them.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] This restriction was dropped in RFC 7158, where a JSON text was redefined as any serialized value.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Numbers in JSON are agnostic with regard to their representation within programming languages.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] While this allows for numbers of arbitrary precision to be serialized, it may lead to portability issues.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] For example, since no differentiation is made between integer and floating-point values, some implementations may treat `42`, `42.0`, and `4.2E+1` as the same number, while others may not.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] The JSON standard makes no requirements regarding implementation details such as overflow, underflow, loss of precision, rounding, or signed zeros, but it does recommend expecting no more than IEEE 754 binary64 precision for "good interoperability".
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] There is no inherent precision loss in serializing a machine-level binary representation of a floating-point number (like binary64) into a human-readable decimal representation (like numbers in JSON) and back; there exist published algorithms to do this conversion exactly and optimally.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Comments were intentionally excluded from JSON.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] JSON disallows "trailing commas", a comma after the last value inside a data structure.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Trailing commas are a common feature of JSON derivatives to improve ease of use.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] RFC 8259 describes certain aspects of JSON syntax that, while legal per the specifications, can cause interoperability problems.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] In 2015, the IETF published RFC 7493, describing the "I-JSON Message Format", a restricted profile of JSON that constrains the syntax and processing of JSON to avoid, as much as possible, these interoperability issues.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] While JSON provides a syntactic framework for data interchange, unambiguous data interchange also requires agreement between producer and consumer on the semantics of specific use of the JSON syntax.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] One example of where such an agreement is necessary is the serialization of data types that are not part of the JSON standard, for example, dates and regular expressions.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] The official MIME type for JSON text is `application/json`, and most modern implementations have adopted this.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Legacy MIME types include `text/json`, `text/x-json`, and `text/javascript`.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] The standard filename extension is .json.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] The JSON standard does not support object references, but an IETF draft standard for JSON-based object references exists.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] JSON-RPC is a remote procedure call (RPC) protocol built on JSON, as a replacement for XML-RPC or SOAP.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] It is a simple protocol that defines only a handful of data types and commands.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] JSON-RPC lets a system send notifications (information to the server that does not require a response) and multiple calls to the server that can be answered out of order.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Asynchronous JavaScript and JSON (or AJAJ) refers to the same dynamic web page methodology as Ajax, but instead of XML, JSON is the data format.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] AJAJ is a web development technique that provides for the ability of a web page to request new data after it has loaded into the web browser.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Typically, it renders new data from the server in response to user actions on that web page.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] For example, what the user types into a search box, client-side code then sends to the server, which immediately responds with a drop-down list of matching database items.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] JSON has seen ad hoc usage as a configuration language.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] In 2012, Douglas Crockford, JSON creator, had this to say about comments in JSON when used as a configuration language: "I know that the lack of comments makes some people sad, but it shouldn't.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Suppose you are using JSON to keep configuration files, which you would like to annotate.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Go ahead and insert all the comments you like.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] MongoDB uses JSON-like data for its document-oriented database.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Some relational databases have added support for native JSON data types, such as JSONB in PostgreSQL and JSON in MySQL.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] This allows developers to insert JSON data directly without having to convert it to another format.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] JSON being a subset of JavaScript can lead to the misconception that it is safe to pass JSON texts to the JavaScript `eval()` function.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] This is not safe, due to certain valid JSON texts, specifically those containing U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR or U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR, not being valid JavaScript code until JavaScript specifications were updated in 2019, and so older engines may not support it.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] To avoid the many pitfalls caused by executing arbitrary code from the Internet, a new function, `JSON.parse()`, was first added to the fifth edition of ECMAScript, which as of 2017 is supported by all major browsers.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] For non-supported browsers, an API-compatible JavaScript library is provided by Douglas Crockford.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] In addition, the TC39 proposal "Subsume JSON" made ECMAScript a strict JSON superset as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Various JSON parser implementations have suffered from denial-of-service attack and mass assignment vulnerability.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] JSON is promoted as a low-overhead alternative to XML as both of these formats have widespread support for creation, reading, and decoding in the real-world situations where they are commonly used.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] XML has been used to describe structured data and to serialize objects.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Various XML-based protocols exist to represent the same kind of data structures as JSON for the same kind of data interchange purposes.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Data can be encoded in XML in several ways.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] The most expansive form using tag pairs results in a much larger (in character count) representation than JSON, but if data is stored in attributes and *short tag* form where the closing tag is replaced with `/>`, the representation is often about the same size as JSON or just a little larger.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] However, an XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] XML separates data from metadata (via the use of elements and attributes), while JSON does not have such a concept.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Another key difference is the addressing of values.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] JSON has objects with a simple key-to-value mapping, whereas in XML addressing happens on *nodes*, each of which receives a unique ID via the XML processor.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Additionally, the XML standard defines a common attribute `xml:id`, that can be used by the user, to set an ID explicitly.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] XML tag names cannot contain any of the characters !"#$%&'()*+,/;<=>?@[\]^`{|}~, nor a space character, and cannot begin with `-`, `.`, or a numeric digit, whereas JSON keys can (even if quotation mark and backslash must be escaped).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] XML values are strings of *characters*, with no built-in type safety.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] XML has the concept of schema, that permits strong typing, user-defined types, predefined tags, and formal structure, allowing for formal validation of an XML stream.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] JSON has several types built-in and has a similar schema concept in JSON Schema.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] XML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Support for comments and other features have been deemed useful, which has led to several nonstandard JSON supersets being created.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Among them are HJSON, HOCON, and JSON5 (which despite its name, is not the fifth version of JSON).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were not strictly compatible.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] For example, escaping a slash `/` with a backslash `\` is valid in JSON, but was not valid in YAML.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] YAML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] There is also an unrelated project called **CSON** ("Cursive Script Object Notation") that is more syntactically similar to JSON.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] JSON5 syntax is supported in some software as an extension of JSON syntax, for instance in SQLite.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/json] Several serialization formats have been built on or from the JSON specification.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] The **.NET** platform (pronounced as "*dot net"*; formerly named **.NET Core**) is a free and open-source, managed computer software framework for Windows, Linux, and macOS operating systems.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] It is a cross-platform successor to the .NET Framework.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] The project is mainly developed by Microsoft employees by way of the .NET Foundation and is today released under an MIT License.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] New versions of the .NET platform are released annually, typically in November.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] The most recent version of .NET is .NET 10, released in November 2025, which is a long-term support (LTS) version, and is scheduled to receive updates until November 2028.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] In the late 1990s, Microsoft began developing a managed code runtime and programming language (C#) which it billed together as part of the ".NET platform", with the core runtime and software libraries comprising the .NET Framework.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] Soon after the announcement of the C# language at the Professional Developers Conference in 2000 and previews of its software became available, Microsoft began a standardization effort through ECMA for what it dubbed the Common Language Infrastructure.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] The company continued development and support of its own implementation as proprietary, closed source software in the meantime.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] Miguel de Icaza describes .NET Core as a "redesigned version of .NET that is based on the simplified version of the class libraries", and Microsoft's Immo Landwerth explained that .NET Core would be "the foundation of all future .NET platforms".
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] At the time of the announcement, the initial release of the .NET Core project had been seeded with a subset of the libraries' source code and coincided with the relicensing of Microsoft's existing .NET reference source away from the restrictions of the Ms-RSL.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] Landwerth acknowledged the disadvantages of the formerly selected shared license, explaining that it made codename Rotor "a non-starter" as a community-developed open source project because it did not meet the criteria of an Open Source Initiative (OSI) approved license.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] .NET Core 1.0 was released on June 27, 2016, along with Microsoft Visual Studio 2015 Update 3, which enables .NET Core development. .NET Core 1.0.4 and .NET Core 1.1.1 were released along with .NET Core Tools 1.0 and Visual Studio 2017 on March 7, 2017.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] .NET Core 2.0 was released on August 14, 2017, along with Visual Studio 2017 15.3, ASP.NET Core 2.0, and Entity Framework Core 2.0. .NET Core 2.1 was released on May 30, 2018.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] NET Core 2.2 was released on December 4, 2018.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] .NET Core 3 was released on September 23, 2019.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] NET Core 3 adds support for Windows desktop application development and significant performance improvements throughout the base library.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] In November 2020, Microsoft released .NET 5.0.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] The "Core" branding was abandoned and version 4.0 was skipped to avoid conflation with .NET Framework, of which the latest releases had all used 4.x versioning for all significant (non-bugfix) releases since 2010.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] .NET Core Runtime roughly uses semantic versioning, the *major.minor.patch* format.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] Major versions are incremented with "significant changes", API-breaking changes, or with the major version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] Minor versions are incremented with the addition of API features, dependencies, or with the minor version increase in an existing dependency.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] Patch versions are given for bug fixes, new platform support, or other changes not included above.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] As of 2019, runtime versions are backwards-compatible within the same major version number.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] For example, .NET Core 2.2 is able to run programs built for .NET Core 2.1.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] Runtime versions in the same minor version.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] This appears to have relaxed since .NET 5.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] A "roll-forward" behavior allows any .NET program to be run on any newer version given the correct settings.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] The SDK does not use semantic versioning.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] As of 2019, it supports targeting *every* runtime version prior to its maximum supported version.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] As of 2020, this extends down to .NET Framework runtimes as well, though downloading an additional "targeting pack" from NuGet may be necessary.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] The major and minor versions of an SDK always matches the major and minor versions of the runtime it contains or is aligned for.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] Alpine Linux, which primarily supports and uses musl libc, is supported since .NET Core 2.1.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] Windows Arm64 is natively supported since .NET 5.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] Previously, .NET on ARM meant applications compiled for the x86 architecture and run through the ARM emulation layer.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] Linux .NET runs on Power ISA to some extent since .NET 7, officially no support is claimed by Microsoft but .NET does contain code for Power ISA compatibility for Linux systems and is able to be compiled for Power ISA systems specifically 64 bit Little Endian variant.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] .NET fully supports C# and F# (and C++/CLI as of 3.1; only enabled on Windows) and supports Visual Basic .NET (for version 15.5 in .NET Core 5.0.100-preview.4, and some old versions supported in old .NET Core).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] VB.NET compiles and runs on .NET, but as of .NET Core 3.1, the separate Visual Basic Runtime is not implemented.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] Microsoft initially announced that .NET Core 3 would include the Visual Basic Runtime, but after two years the timeline for such support was updated to .NET 5.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] .NET supports the following cross-platform scenarios: ASP.NET Core web apps, command-line/console apps, libraries and Universal Windows Platform apps.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] Prior to .NET Core 3.0, it did not implement Windows Forms or Windows Presentation Foundation (WPF), which render the standard GUI for desktop software on Windows.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] However, from .NET Core 3 on, it started implementing them along with Universal Windows Platform (UWP).
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] It was also possible to write cross-platform graphical applications using .NET with the GTK# language-binding for the GTK widget toolkit, but this binding has not been maintained for many years.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] Unlike .NET Framework, which is serviced using Windows Update, .NET used to rely on its package manager to receive updates.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] Since December 2020, however, .NET updates started being delivered via Windows Update as well.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] NuGet serves as the primary distribution mechanism for libraries and tools in the .NET ecosystem, including third-party components that extend core functionality.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] Among these are ADO.NET-compatible data providers, which offer database connectivity for systems beyond the default SQL Server support.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] These providers enable direct access to databases such as Oracle, MySQL, PostgreSQL, and others, and are commonly used in applications that require cross-platform data access, integration with ORM technologies, or support for specific database features.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] The two main components of .NET are CoreCLR and CoreFX, which are comparable to the Common Language Runtime (CLR) and the Framework Class Library (FCL) of the .NET Framework's Common Language Infrastructure (CLI) implementation.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] As an implementation of CLI's Standard Libraries, CoreFX shares a subset of .NET Framework APIs, however, it also comes with its own APIs that are not part of the .NET Framework.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] A variant of the .NET library is used for UWP.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] The .NET command-line interface offers an execution entry point for operating systems and provides developer services like compilation and package management.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] The official community mascot of .NET is the .NET Bot (stylized as "dotnet bot" or "dotnet-bot").
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] The dotnet bot served as the placeholder developer for the initial check-in of the .NET source code when it was open-sourced.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/net] It has since been used as the official mascot.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] In computer science, **reflective programming** or **reflection** is the ability of a process to examine, introspect, and modify its own structure and behavior.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] The earliest computers were programmed in their native assembly languages, which were inherently reflective, as these original architectures could be programmed by defining instructions as data and using self-modifying code.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] As the bulk of programming moved to higher-level compiled languages such as ALGOL, COBOL, Fortran, Pascal, and C, this reflective ability largely disappeared until new programming languages with reflection built into their type systems appeared.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] Brian Cantwell Smith's 1982 doctoral dissertation introduced the notion of computational reflection in procedural programming languages and the notion of the meta-circular interpreter as a component of 3-Lisp.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection helps programmers make generic software libraries to display data, process different formats of data, perform serialization and deserialization of data for communication, or do bundling and unbundling of data for containers or bursts of communication.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] Reflective systems may provide a mirror type, used as a decoupled reflection of an object or identifier.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] Effective use of reflection almost always requires a plan: A design framework, encoding description, object library, a map of a database or entity relations.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection makes a language more suited to network-oriented code.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] For example, it assists languages such as Java to operate well in networks by enabling libraries for serialization, bundling and varying data formats.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] Languages without reflection such as C are required to use auxiliary compilers for tasks like Abstract Syntax Notation to produce code for serialization and bundling.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection can be used for observing and modifying program execution at runtime.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] A reflection-oriented program component can monitor the execution of an enclosure of code and can modify itself according to a desired goal of that enclosure.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] This is typically accomplished by dynamically assigning program code at runtime.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] In object-oriented programming languages such as Java, reflection allows *inspection* of classes, interfaces, fields and methods at runtime without knowing the names of the interfaces, fields, methods at compile time.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] It also allows *instantiation* of new objects and *invocation* of methods.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection is often used as part of software testing, such as for the runtime creation/instantiation of mock objects.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection is also a key strategy for metaprogramming.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] In some object-oriented programming languages such as C# and Java, reflection can be used to bypass member accessibility rules.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] For C#-properties this can be achieved by writing directly onto the (usually invisible) backing field of a non-public property.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] It is also possible to find non-public methods of classes and types and manually invoke them.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] This works for project-internal files as well as external libraries such as .NET's assemblies and Java's archives.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] A language that supports reflection provides a number of features available at runtime that would otherwise be difficult to accomplish in a lower-level language.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] These features can be implemented in different ways.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] In MOO, reflection forms a natural part of everyday programming idiom.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] When verbs (methods) are called, various variables such as `verb` (the name of the verb being called) and `this` (the object on which the verb is called) are populated to give the context of the call.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] Compiled languages rely on their runtime system to provide information about the source code.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] A compiled Objective-C executable, for example, records the names of all methods in a block of the executable, providing a table to correspond these with the underlying methods (or selectors for these methods) compiled into the program.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] In a compiled language that supports runtime creation of functions, such as Common Lisp, the runtime environment must include a compiler or an interpreter.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection can be implemented for languages without built-in reflection by using a program transformation system to define automated source-code changes.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection may allow a user to create unexpected control flow paths through an application, potentially bypassing security measures.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] Historical vulnerabilities in Java caused by unsafe reflection allowed code retrieved from potentially untrusted remote machines to break out of the Java sandbox security mechanism.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] A large scale study of 120 Java vulnerabilities in 2013 concluded that unsafe reflection is the most common vulnerability in Java, though not the most exploited.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] Runtime reflection systems introduce a non-negligible runtime performance overhead.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] For instance, in Java, because reflective operations are resolved dynamically at execution time, many compiler and JVM optimizations—such as method inlining, static binding, and aggressive just-in-time specialization—cannot be fully applied.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] As a consequence, reflective calls are typically slower than their statically resolved counterparts.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] In sequential applications, reflection can significantly increase execution time and memory consumption when used in performance-critical code paths.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] In multithreaded applications, reflective implementations generally preserve scalability, but still exhibit noticeably higher absolute execution times—commonly between 1.5x and 10× slower—than equivalent non-reflective code.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] In languages like C++ and Rust, reflection is performed at compile time.
[src:newtonsoft-json-dotnet/reflection-computer-programming] Compile-time reflection systems are weaker than runtime reflection systems like those of Java and C#, but incur no runtime overhead due to being performed during compilation.
